Time Limit: 4 sec
Memory: 256 MB

Description

You have been given an array A of N integers and M ranges. The i-th range is defined by the two integers li and ri, where li ≤ ri.

Initially, array S is empty. For range i, add elements

A[li], A[li+1], ..., A[ri]

into the array S. After adding all the elements from each of the ranges, sort the elements of S in ascending order.

You need to answer Q queries. Each query consists of a number K > 0. You have to find the K-th smallest element in S, i.e., the element at the K-th position in sorted S.

It may be possible that the same element appears multiple times in S.

Input Format

The first line of the input contains a single integer T — the number of test cases (1 ≤ T ≤ 10).

Then T test cases follow.

The first line of each test case contains three integers N, M, and Q (1 ≤ N, M, Q ≤ 10^5).

The second line contains N space-separated integers

A1, A2, ..., AN

the elements of the array A, where 1 ≤ Ai ≤ 10^9.

Next M lines contain two space-separated integers li and ri — the i-th range, where

1 ≤ li ≤ ri ≤ N.

The last line of a test case contains Q space-separated integers

K1, K2, ..., KQ

where Ki denotes the i-th query and

1 ≤ Ki ≤ 10^18.

Output Format

For each test case, print Q space-separated integers, where the i-th number denotes the answer of the i-th query.

If the K-th value doesn't exist for a particular query, print -1.

Constraints

* 1 ≤ T ≤ 10
* 1 ≤ N, M, Q ≤ 10^5
* 1 ≤ Ai ≤ 10^9
* 1 ≤ li ≤ ri ≤ N
* 1 ≤ Ki ≤ 10^18

It's guaranteed that the sum of N over all test cases is reasonable for the given limits.

Sample Input 1

```text
2
3 3 4
1 3 2
1 3
2 3
1 1
1 2 5 8
4 2 3
1 5 4 3
1 4
1 3
1 5 7
```

Sample Output 1

```text
1 1 3 -1
1 4 5
```

Note

Test case 1:

After adding the ranges,

S = {1, 3, 2, 3, 2, 1}

After sorting,

S = {1, 1, 2, 2, 3, 3}

Queries ask for the 1st, 2nd, 5th, and 8th elements.

The answers are 1, 1, 3, and -1 (the 8th element does not exist).

Test case 2:

After adding the ranges,

S = {1, 5, 4, 3, 1, 5, 4}

After sorting,

S = {1, 1, 3, 4, 4, 5, 5}

Queries ask for the 1st, 5th, and 7th elements.

The answers are 1, 4, and 5.



#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

typedef long long ll;

void solve()
{
    int N, M, Q;
    cin >> N >> M >> Q;

    vector<ll> A(N + 1);

    for (int i = 1; i <= N; i++)
        cin >> A[i];

    vector<ll> diff(N + 3, 0);

    for (int i = 0; i < M; i++)
    {
        int l, r;
        cin >> l >> r;

        diff[l]++;
        diff[r + 1]--;
    }

    vector<pair<ll,ll>> v;

    ll cur = 0;

    for (int i = 1; i <= N; i++)
    {
        cur += diff[i];

        if (cur > 0)
            v.push_back({A[i], cur});
    }

    sort(v.begin(), v.end());

    vector<ll> pref(v.size());
    vector<ll> values(v.size());

    for (int i = 0; i < (int)v.size(); i++)
    {
        values[i] = v[i].first;

        pref[i] = v[i].second;

        if (i)
            pref[i] += pref[i - 1];
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < Q; i++)
    {
        long long K;
        cin >> K;

        if (pref.empty() || K > pref.back())
        {
            cout << -1;
        }
        else
        {
            int idx = lower_bound(pref.begin(), pref.end(), K) - pref.begin();
            cout << values[idx];
        }

        if (i + 1 < Q)
            cout << ' ';
    }

    cout << '\n';
}

int main()
{
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int T;
    cin >> T;

    while (T--)
        solve();

    return 0;
}
